{"questionId":"9067161","questionHtml":"<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Aspirin can be obtained from salicylic acid.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Unreacted salicylic acid may be present as an impurity in aspirin and can be detected in the infrared (IR) spectrum.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/c71e70c2fda72d0896c3ac7ae56477b3cff6e43e.png\" width=\"392\" height=\"175\"></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Name the functional group and identify the absorption band that differentiates salicylic acid from aspirin. Use section 26 of the data booklet.</span></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Name:&nbsp;</span></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Absorption band:</span></span></p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><em>Name</em>:<br>hydroxyl&nbsp; <strong>[✔]</strong></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><em>Absorption band</em>:<br>3200–3600 «cm<sup>–1</sup>»&nbsp; <strong>[✔]</strong></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><strong>Note:</strong>&nbsp;Accept “phenol” <strong>OR</strong> “alcohol” but <strong>not</strong> “hydroxide”.</span></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9067161","referenceCode":"19M.3.sl.TZ1.14","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"Aspirin can be obtained from salicylic acid. Unreacted salicylic acid may be present as an impurity in aspirin and can be detected in the infrared (IR) spectrum. Name the functiona","paper":"3","level":"sl","questionNumber":"14","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Options","Options","D: Medicinal chemistry","D.2 Aspirin and penicillin","Options","D: Medicinal chemistry"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}